WEBVTT

00:01.760 --> 00:04.354
l just wanna be clear
that l am here as a last resort.

00:04.520 --> 00:05.839
l understand.

00:06.000 --> 00:08.912
l don't have a lot of faith in psychiatry
as a science.

00:09.920 --> 00:12.832
l think some of the drugs you're pushing
are interesting.

00:14.160 --> 00:17.994
And l'm all for messing around
with brain chemistry.

00:18.440 --> 00:21.000
l mean, that's how
l got through high school.

00:22.000 --> 00:26.232
But in my experience, popping pills
doesn't relieve social anxiety. . .

00:26.400 --> 00:30.154
. . .quite as well as, say,
bourbon and Marvin Gaye.

00:30.800 --> 00:34.190
No, l get it. You're desperate,
and l'm full of hooey.

00:36.040 --> 00:40.238
So in the words of Marvin Gaye,
what's going on?

00:41.080 --> 00:45.392
-Everything l say is confidential, right?
-Whatever you say stays in this room.

00:45.560 --> 00:46.788
Kind of like Vegas.

00:46.960 --> 00:49.235
Well, except there's no way
you're leaving here. . .

00:49.400 --> 00:52.312
. . .with more money
than when you came in.

00:53.080 --> 00:55.275
Yeah, like Vegas.

00:57.120 --> 01:01.033
Anyway, last night l'm out
with my stupid, lame-ass brother.

01:01.200 --> 01:04.351
Sounds like
you've got some anger towards him.

01:04.519 --> 01:06.715
Oh, you're good.

01:08.920 --> 01:12.310
This is nice.
You and me, spending time together.

01:12.480 --> 01:15.153
-Why don't we do this more often?
-l don't have an answer.

01:15.320 --> 01:18.756
Well, me neither.
So how long till the movie starts?

01:18.920 --> 01:20.273
About 20 minutes.

01:20.440 --> 01:23.716
Yeah, sure, 20 minutes
not counting previews and ads. . .

01:23.880 --> 01:26.553
. . .the popcorn and the giant pretzel
holding hands. . .

01:26.720 --> 01:30.395
. . .the big soda drinking the little soda,
which, frankly, is cannibalism. . .

01:30.560 --> 01:33.358
. . .and the reminder
to turn off your cell phones and shut up.

01:33.520 --> 01:36.717
But nobody does, because good manners
are just the latest casualty. . .

01:36.880 --> 01:39.474
. . .in the ongoing collapse
of Western civilization.

01:39.640 --> 01:41.995
l now have an answer.

01:44.480 --> 01:47.199
-l miss Jake.
-How can you miss him?

01:47.360 --> 01:49.669
We just dropped him off
at his friend's house.

01:49.840 --> 01:52.832
By the way, if you get tired
of those magazines under your bed. . .

01:53.000 --> 01:55.468
. . .the kid's mom looked fairly doable.

01:55.640 --> 01:59.235
Forget the mom. Did you see how happy
Jake was spending the weekend away?

01:59.400 --> 02:00.549
Why would you think that?

02:00.720 --> 02:03.393
Just because he jumped out of the car
while it was moving?

02:03.560 --> 02:08.076
Alan, he was happy to see his friends.
Being away from you is just gravy.

02:08.240 --> 02:11.550
l know, l know. lt's natural
for him to want to spend more time. . .

02:11.720 --> 02:13.551
. . .with his peers than his parents.

02:13.720 --> 02:16.871
But all the same, it's sad.

02:17.040 --> 02:19.918
Yeah, sunrise, sunset.

02:21.480 --> 02:23.550
One day you're holding a baby
in your arms. . .

02:23.720 --> 02:26.757
. . .and the next day he's off
hawking loogies and lighting farts. . .

02:26.920 --> 02:29.832
. . .with a bunch of
Ritalin-addled sixth graders.

02:30.240 --> 02:32.310
Why do l bother
to share my feelings with you?

02:32.480 --> 02:34.789
l don't know.
lt's not like l encourage it.

02:35.720 --> 02:38.837
Oh, come on, so your kid
doesn't need you like he used to.

02:39.000 --> 02:40.353
That's a good thing.

02:40.520 --> 02:43.239
You can spend your weekends
enjoying yourself.

02:43.680 --> 02:47.355
That's true. l mean, there are things
l wanna do that l haven't had time for.

02:47.520 --> 02:49.351
Like that kid's mom.

02:49.520 --> 02:52.193
No, no, l mean like-- Like reading.

02:52.360 --> 02:54.112
Finally cracking open the classics.

02:54.280 --> 02:57.670
Alan, if you wanna crack something
open, l recommend that kid's mom.

02:58.440 --> 02:59.634
No, no, l'm serious.

02:59.800 --> 03:02.553
You know, for years
l have been wishing that l had time. . .

03:02.720 --> 03:04.438
. . .to read all the great books.

03:04.600 --> 03:09.390
You know, Dostoyevsky
and Hemingway. . .

03:09.560 --> 03:13.155
. . .Faulkner and Dickens
and Shakespeare.

03:13.320 --> 03:14.355
And history, history.

03:14.520 --> 03:18.559
U.S.-- U.S. history, world history,
the history of language.

03:18.720 --> 03:21.757
l mean, why doesn't anyone
speak Sumerian anymore?

03:23.160 --> 03:25.833
l don't know,
because l haven't read the book.

03:26.880 --> 03:32.352
And, oh, poetry, poetry.
Byron and Keats and Shelley.

03:32.520 --> 03:34.078
And biographies.

03:34.240 --> 03:37.789
Julius Caesar and Abraham Lincoln
and, oh, Groucho Marx.

03:37.960 --> 03:42.272
l mean-- l mean, look at them all.
Look at them, they're mocking me.

03:42.440 --> 03:43.873
l haven't read any of them.

03:44.040 --> 03:46.759
Okay, well, just pick one for now.

03:46.920 --> 03:48.751
Why bother? There's not enough time.

03:48.920 --> 03:51.434
There's too many books,
and there's not enough time.

03:51.600 --> 03:54.353
Maybe you just need a system.
Put a book next to the toilet.

03:54.520 --> 03:56.795
Every couple of days,
knock out a couple chapters.

03:56.960 --> 03:59.190
No, no, it's too late for me.

03:59.360 --> 04:02.477
There's not enough
bowel movements left.

04:05.560 --> 04:08.597
-Maybe you need to change your diet.
-No, it's hopeless.

04:08.760 --> 04:10.955
Jake will be grown up soon
and l'll be dead.

04:11.120 --> 04:12.917
And you know
what l'll have left behind?

04:13.080 --> 04:16.629
A life of unfulfilled dreams,
a shelf of unread books. . .

04:16.800 --> 04:20.394
. . .and three unopened seasons
of Six Feet Under on DVD.

04:23.280 --> 04:25.669
So, what are you doing tonight?

04:32.360 --> 04:33.349
All right.

04:33.520 --> 04:36.876
So your brother had a panic attack
in the middle of a bookstore.

04:37.360 --> 04:39.157
How'd that make you feel?

04:39.840 --> 04:42.877
What the hell do my feelings
have to do with anything?

04:43.040 --> 04:45.429
Why don't you just humor me?

04:46.240 --> 04:48.117
Well, l felt a little ashamed.

04:48.280 --> 04:50.794
Because you felt
that his behavior reflected on you?

04:50.960 --> 04:53.315
No, because l left him there.

04:54.360 --> 04:55.679
You left him?

04:56.640 --> 04:59.712
Not permanently.
l came back and got him. . .

04:59.880 --> 05:02.633
. . .after he was all cried out
and it was time for the movie.

05:02.800 --> 05:04.313
So you still went to the movie?

05:04.480 --> 05:07.517
Yeah, l bought the tickets online.
They don't refund those.

05:14.440 --> 05:16.158
Red Vine?

05:17.080 --> 05:20.914
No, thank you. l am so sorry.
l don't know what came over me.

05:21.080 --> 05:24.356
Who among us hasn't collapsed,
weeping, in the middle of a bookstore. . .

05:24.520 --> 05:26.317
. . .for no apparent reason?

05:26.800 --> 05:29.109
You know, l think
maybe l'd be better off at home.

05:29.680 --> 05:31.511
So l'm supposed to miss the movie. . .

05:31.680 --> 05:34.114
. . .just because
you had a nervous breakdown?

05:34.280 --> 05:35.838
Well, kind of.

05:36.280 --> 05:38.669
Don't you think
that's a little selfish, Alan?

05:39.720 --> 05:44.589
lt's just, all of a sudden l felt crushed
by this unbelievable sense of grief. . .

05:44.760 --> 05:48.594
. . .like my entire life has been an exercise
in pathetic futility.

05:48.760 --> 05:50.910
Well, l wouldn't rule it out.

05:52.240 --> 05:54.276
Come on, bunky, cheer up.
Have a Red Vine.

05:54.440 --> 05:55.998
l don't want a Red Vine.

05:56.160 --> 05:57.639
-Sno-Cap?
-No.

05:57.800 --> 05:59.279
-Raisinet?
-No.

05:59.440 --> 06:01.112
-Goobers?
-How much crap did you buy?

06:01.280 --> 06:02.793
They couldn't change a hundred.

06:06.240 --> 06:08.435
All right, l'll have a Junior Mint.

06:09.320 --> 06:10.753
l didn't get Junior Mints.

06:12.600 --> 06:15.398
Of course not. Story of my life.

06:15.560 --> 06:18.950
No Junior Mints for Alan.
Just Goobers.

06:19.120 --> 06:20.872
Goobers, Goobers, Goobers.

06:21.040 --> 06:23.952
-Dude, dude, you need to be quiet.
-Why? Why?

06:24.120 --> 06:27.271
The First Amendment gives me
the right to yell in a crowded theater.

06:27.440 --> 06:29.396
Goobers!

06:30.440 --> 06:31.873
Hey, look, movie quiz.

06:32.040 --> 06:34.918
-Let's play the movie quiz.
-l don't wanna play the movie quiz.

06:35.080 --> 06:37.548
-lt'll be fun. l'll bet you're good at it.
-All right.

06:37.720 --> 06:40.871
''Debra Winger and Richard Gere
starred in An Officer and a blank. ''

06:41.040 --> 06:44.749
-Oh, please.
-You need a hint?

06:45.200 --> 06:47.998
-There's a hint in the corner.
-No, l don't need a hint.

06:48.160 --> 06:50.879
l know the answer.
Everybody here knows the answer.

06:51.040 --> 06:52.917
Everybody on the planet
knows the answer.

06:53.080 --> 06:55.640
-We're not stupid.
-Chill, chill.

06:55.800 --> 06:57.677
Oh, wait.
Oh, here's another brainteaser.

06:57.840 --> 07:00.195
''Steven Spielberg
directed this modern retelling. . .

07:00.360 --> 07:03.830
. . .of the H.G. Wells classic
War of the blank. ''

07:04.000 --> 07:07.037
-Couch. War of the Couch.
-Stop it.

07:07.200 --> 07:09.998
Oh, wait, no, no, l got it.
War of the Blow-It-Out-Your-Ass.

07:10.160 --> 07:12.833
You know what? Maybe you're right.
Maybe we should go.

07:13.000 --> 07:14.399
Oh, wait, no, l know this one.

07:14.560 --> 07:17.358
''Johnny Depp cruised to success
in this comedy-action film. . .

07:17.520 --> 07:19.397
. . .inspired by a Disneyland attraction. ''

07:19.560 --> 07:21.915
Pirates of the Blow-It-Out-Your-Ass.

07:22.080 --> 07:23.672
He's-- He's behind on his reading.

07:23.840 --> 07:27.276
Oh, and let's not forget Judy Garland
in that immortal classic. . .

07:27.440 --> 07:30.989
... The Wizard of Blow-It-Out-Your-Ass.

07:31.160 --> 07:34.948
That sounds like quite an episode.
ls your brother seeing a therapist?

07:35.120 --> 07:36.951
How would l know?

07:37.120 --> 07:39.839
He's your brother. He lives with you.

07:40.000 --> 07:41.592
So?

07:42.640 --> 07:44.835
All right, go ahead.

07:45.000 --> 07:47.912
Just because l took him in,
doesn't mean l listen to him.

07:48.080 --> 07:49.149
l understand.

07:49.320 --> 07:52.392
He just whines about the same crap
over and over.

07:52.560 --> 07:55.279
-Okay.
-lt's not even interesting crap.

07:56.960 --> 07:59.679
lt's the crap
that bores the crap out of crap.

07:59.840 --> 08:02.229
l got it. lt's crap. Go ahead.

08:02.400 --> 08:06.916
Thank you.
So we're driving home, and. . . .

08:14.520 --> 08:16.590
This seat is very comfortable.

08:16.760 --> 08:20.514
Genuine leather, nine-way adjustable,
lumbar support. lt's. . . .

08:20.680 --> 08:24.150
l wish l'd have spent a few extra bucks
and gotten the ejection package.

08:25.080 --> 08:28.868
-l said l was sorry.
-They don't refund those tickets, Alan.

08:31.400 --> 08:34.551
-l wanna go see Jake.
-Why? He's at a sleepover.

08:34.720 --> 08:37.518
l've just got this feeling
that he needs me.

08:37.679 --> 08:39.671
You mean
like some sort of telepathic thing?

08:39.840 --> 08:42.195
-Exactly.
-l see.

08:44.360 --> 08:46.396
-Did you know l was gonna do that?
-No.

08:46.560 --> 08:49.472
Then l wouldn't trust
your psychic powers.

08:50.080 --> 08:52.833
Oh, come on.
We can just stop by for a few minutes.

08:53.000 --> 08:55.992
We have time now,
since we decided to skip the movie.

08:56.160 --> 09:00.278
Oh, we decided that, did we? That's
the way it went down for you, huh?

09:00.440 --> 09:02.396
That's how
you interpret recent events?

09:03.200 --> 09:05.668
Settle down.
You're acting like a crazy person.

09:05.840 --> 09:10.356
Me? l'm acting like a crazy person?
Are you freaking kidding me?

09:10.520 --> 09:14.069
Listen to yourself.
You're getting a little scary right now.

09:16.320 --> 09:18.880
Okay, fine. You wanna see the kid,
we'll go see the kid.

09:19.040 --> 09:20.553
Thank you.

09:21.320 --> 09:22.799
Was that so hard?

09:28.840 --> 09:31.832
Charlie? The road.

09:35.960 --> 09:37.678
Please?

09:41.640 --> 09:43.073
You know, when you have kids. . .

09:43.240 --> 09:45.470
. . .you find there's a deep,
spiritual connection.

09:45.640 --> 09:48.632
You feel an actual tug
when your child needs you.

09:48.800 --> 09:51.997
lnteresting. What do you feel
when your brother hates you?

09:54.000 --> 09:55.797
Alan. ls everything okay?

09:55.960 --> 09:58.349
Oh, yeah, fine.
l just need to see Jake for a minute.

09:58.520 --> 10:00.715
-He's feeling a tug.
-A tug?

10:00.880 --> 10:03.713
Or it could be gas. We're not sure.

10:04.720 --> 10:06.153
Well, could you just call Jake?

10:06.320 --> 10:10.950
Jake, your father's here!
Put that down, Timmy!

10:11.120 --> 10:13.998
-What?
-l just wanted to see if you were okay.

10:15.480 --> 10:17.914
Oh, great, now l'm dead.
Thanks a lot.

10:18.680 --> 10:21.717
lt doesn't count.
l was talking to my stupid dad.

10:23.360 --> 10:26.557
Well, it-- lt seems like
you've got everything under control here.

10:26.720 --> 10:28.392
Actually, l ran out of ice cream.

10:28.560 --> 10:31.552
Do you think you could keep an eye
on the kids for a few minutes?

10:31.720 --> 10:34.234
-Well--
-Thanks a million. l'll be right back.

